aspace_helpers.title: Add post-processing to 6xx's in aspace2alma collection-level process

comments.body: Thanks Phoebe. I'll take a look and see what we can do via post-processing the data.

a couple of clarifications to Phoebe's messages (which were paraphrased from our slack conversation) :) 

A couple of edits:
The ASpace MARC exporter is generating 6xx $2 codes that are not valid. **The main type is $2 viaf because we use viaf identifiers/URIs in ArchivesSpace but there isn't an approved $2 code in for viaf.** The list of valid codes is here : https://www.loc.gov/standards/sourcelist/subject.html
It also creates 6xx _7 $2 uncontrolled. The correct format would be 6xx _4 with no $2 for an uncontrolled heading: https://www.loc.gov/marc/bibliographic/bd600.html
However, 6xx _4 doesn't show up in Blacklight, so we would really want to change them all to 6xx _0 even though some of the names are not valid LCSH
We don't want to add 6xx _4 because there are a lot of other libraries' local vocabularies in various records that are coded that way.
**We do want to retain the $0 for the viaf headings.**

figgy.title: Can't load structure manager on a resource

comments.body:
We investigated the object in question and found that it has 37 leaf structure nodes that hold proxy objects with ids for (FileSet) resources that have been deleted.

Relevant code: 
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/0ee595585c6e94d686f29790084445892830797b/app/views/base/_structure_node.html.erb#L22-L25

The array holds the proxy object, but when the code goes to fetch the object it comes back nil, so the thumbnail errors.

Code we used to discover this state:
```ruby
id = "cfa08806-5a73-4920-9bcc-2c9df295dd38"
r = ChangeSetPersister.default.query_service.find_by(id: id)
change_set = ChangeSet.for(r)
logical_order = change_set.logical_structure.first
members = Wayfinder.for(change_set.resource).members_with_parents
logical_order = WithProxyForObject.new(logical_order, members)
def add_leaves(a, nodes)                                                                                                                                             
   nodes.each do |node|                                                                                                                                               
     if node.nodes.empty?                                                                                                                                             
       a << node                                                                                                                                                      
     else                                                                                                                                                             
       add_leaves(a, node.nodes)                                                                                                                                      
     end                                                                                                                                                              
   end                                                                                                                                                                
 end                                                                                                                                                                  
 leaves = []                                                                                                                                                          
 add_leaves(leaves, logical_order.nodes) 
```

Note that the resource didn't have any members in its member ids list that had been deleted, just the proxy nodes.

Possible next steps:
- Figure out how these logical nodes persisted after their proxy objects were deleted and prevent that from happening
- Change the code to check `proxy_for_object` instead of `proxy.present?`
- Delete these dead nodes on this resource.
https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/use_catalog_jsonld/app/change_set_persisters/change_set_persister/cleanup_structure.rb should be what gets run when a file set is deleted.

Could we filter out dead nodes when we load them in the controller? Then if/when the structure is saved again they would get cleaned up.

Or maybe a setter in the change set
That's a cool idea.
Probably optimistic locking would be the way to prevent this. But might cause a problem for the user if they do a bunch of work and then can't save it.

figgy.title: Try adding optimistic locking to Figgy resources

comments.body:
Consider what impact this might have on users.

Potentially try not using the lock in form? This is what we do with FileSets.

One idea is to code in a configuration switch that allows us to switch off optimistic locking in the forms if we want to try it for a while. Then if there are are user complaints we can quickly turn it off.

pdc_describe.title: When I add files in S3 they never show up

comments.body:
I apologize, https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/blob/main/app/models/work.rb#L118 is likely where this bug originates. If there are no changes to the `state` of the `Work`, S3 resources are *not* synchronized to the ActiveStorage attachments on the `Work`. However, if the `Work` has not yet been persisted, then the S3 resources are also not synchronized.

This behavior is undesirable, and I suspect that this was related to a bug found when attempting to synchronize S3 resources for the `Work` before it had been persisted.
